{"title_page": "Poli\u00e7an, Gjirokast\u00ebr", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement AL\n|type               = v\n|official_name      = Poli\u00e7an\n|other_name         = \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03b7\n|image_flag         = \n|image_shield       = \n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_location     = \n|county             = [[Gjirokast\u00ebr County|Gjirokast\u00ebr]]\n|municipality       = [[Dropull]]\n|municunit          = [[Pogon, Albania|Pogon]]\n|leader_name        = \n|leader_party       = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|40|7|53|N|20|21|2|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = \n|population_as_of   = \n|population_total   = \n|postal_code        = \n|area_code          = \n|car_plates         = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Poli\u00e7an''' ({{lang-gr|\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03b7|Polytsani}}) is an ethnic Greek village in [[Gjirokast\u00ebr County]], southern [[Albania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geonames.org/search.html?q=Dervi\u00e7an&country=AL|accessdate=3 September 2010|title=Location of Dervi\u00e7an}}</ref> At the 2015 local government reform it became part of the municipality [[Dropull]].<ref>[http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf Law nr. 115/2014] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> It is within the wider Pogoni region that stretches in both [[Greece]] and Albania.<ref name=Giakoumis15/> Poli\u00e7an was the municipal center of the former [[Pogon, Albania|Pogon]] municipality in Albania. It is nicknamed \"the Bride of the Pogoni region\".<ref name=enet>{{cite web|last1=\u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5|first1=\u03a3\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03b1|title=\u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bb\u03b5\u03b3\u03b3\u03cd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03b7 \u03a0\u03c9\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03af\u03bf\u03c5|url=http://www.enet.gr/?i=news.el.article&id=444909|website=enet.gr|publisher=Eleftherotypia|accessdate=3 February 2015|language=Greek}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Antiquity and Byzantine period===\nIn classical antiquity the region was inhabited by the [[Chaonians]],<ref name=Giakoumis12/> one of the three major [[Ancient Greeks|Greek]] tribes that inhabited [[Epirus (ancient state)|ancient Epirus]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boardman|first1=John|last2=Hammond|first2=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=The Cambridge Ancient History - The Expansion of the Greek World, Eighth to Sixth Centuries B.C., Part 3: Volume 3|edition=Second|location=Cambridge, United Kingdom|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1982|isbn=0-521-23447-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qAoqP4g1fEC|ref=harv|pages=430, 434}}</ref> Polican was identified with the Chaonian settlement ''Politeiani'' ({{lang-el|\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u03ae}}) also known as ''Polyani'' ({{lang-el|\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03b1\u03bd\u03ae}}). The name appears to be borrowed from the nearby mountain Polyainos.<ref name=Giakoumis12/> Ancient coins depicting [[Alexander the Great]] have been unearthed in Poli\u00e7an.<ref>Hammond, 1967, [https://books.google.gr/books?ei=0yfRVKysCInyUKjCgMgB&hl=el&id=kEFoAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Polican%22+%22alexander+the+great%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Alexander+the+Great+at+Polican%2C+Vagalat+and+Phoenice%2C+later+kings+at+Dodona+and+Preveza%22 p. 722]</ref>\n\nThe ancient name has changed to the present form (Polyts(i)ani) during the [[Slavs|Slavic]] invasion (7th-8th century).<ref name=Giakoumis12>Giakoumis, 2009, p. 12</ref> In the late [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] period (11th-15th century) two Christian Orthodox monasteries were erected next to Polican.<ref name=Giakoumis12/> After the Fall of [[Constantinople]] in the [[Fourth Crusade]] (1204), Polican became part of the Roman State of [[Despotate of Epirus]] and refuge for various Byzantine noble families.<ref name=Giakoumis141>Giakoumis, 2009, p. 141</ref>\n\n===Ottoman period===\nAt the period of [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] occupation, that started in mid-15th century, Polican enjoyed a privileged semi-autonomous status which led to economic and cultural flourishing.<ref name=Giakoumis141/> The settlement was included in the [[Koinon of the Zagorisians|Koinon of Zagori]], although geographically it was not part of the [[Zagori]] region, but belonged to the Pogoni villages.<ref name=Giakoumis15>Giakoumis, 2009, p. 15</ref>\n\n[[File:Politsani Epirus 1931.jpg|thumbnail|Religious festival next to the church of Saint Nicholas in Polican, 1931]]\nIn the early 16th century two significant church buildings were erected in the town: Saint Athanasius (1513) and Saint Demetrius (1526). Both of them display unique features of early post-Byzantine art.<ref>Giakoumis, 2009, p. 139</ref> A Greek school was founded in 1672 by the local Orthodox missionary [[Sophianos of Dryinoupolis|Sophianos]] next to the church of Saint Athanasius.<ref name=Koltsida131>Koltsida, 2008, p. 131</ref> The school attracted also students from the nearby regions next to [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]] ([[Zagori, Albania|Zagori]] and Riza).<ref>Koltsida, 2008, p. 197</ref>\n\nA second school started operating in 1750, sponsored by a local businessman and benefactor.<ref name=Koltsida131/> Greek education was expanded with the foundation of two secondary level schools in 1866, in addition to a boys' and a girls' school in 1866 and 1874 respectively.<ref>Koltsida, 2008, p. 229</ref> The local educational institutions became renowned to such a degree that their graduates were eligible for admission to any Greek college in the Ottoman capital [[Constantinople]] ([[Istanbul]]) without qualifying examinations.<ref>Koltsida, 2008, p. 235</ref> The schools of Polican were financed by the local community and especially by local businessmen and benefactors as well as by the town's diaspora.<ref>Koltsida, 2008, pp. 281&ndash;285</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nPolican and the rest of the settlements in the Pogon municipality became part of [[Albania]] in the 1920s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=(Eds.)|first1=Andreas Hemming ...|title=Albania : family, society and culture in the 20th century|date=2010|publisher=LIT|location=M\u00fcnster [u.a.]|isbn=9783643501448|page=103|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=HfpTqhlsCtMC&pg=PA103}}</ref> In 1940, when [[Kingdom of Italy|Axis Italy]] launched a [[Greco-Italian War|failed invasion against Greece]] from Albanian territory during [[World War II]], the town came under the control of the [[II Army Corps (Greece)|II Army Corps]] of the Greek forces.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carr|first1=John C.|title=The defence and fall of Greece 1940-1941|date=2013|isbn=9781781591819|pages=82\u201383|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=2Zb9AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA82&dq=1940+polican&hl=el&sa=X&ei=aTfOVKf8C8z3UuXtgdAB&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=1940%20polican&f=false}}</ref>\n\nThe Greek communities that reside in Pogon have a recognized minority status by the Albanian state.<ref>Tziovas, 2003, [https://books.google.gr/books?ei=qn_WVMDwKtPkaMq6goAC&hl=el&id=s1VpAAAAMAAJ&dq=pogon+greek+minority&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Apart+from+the+ethnic+Greek+communities+that+are+officially+recognized+as+a+minority+and+comprise+a+clear+and+largely+homogeneous+zone%2C+namely+the+rural+areas+of+Dropul%2C+Sarandi+and+Pogon%2C+the+situation+is+still+quite+complex+in+terms+of%22 p. 196]</ref> A Greek elementary school is currently operating in Polican.<ref>{{cite web|title=Second Report Submitted by Albania Pursuant to Article 25, Paragraph 2 of the Framework onvention for the Protection of National Minorities|url=https://www.coe.int/t/dghl/monitoring/minorities/3_FCNMdocs/PDF_2nd_SR_Albania_en.pdf|website=Council of Europe|accessdate=7 February 2015|page=62}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 1913 the population of Polican  was 1,650 (Greek census).<ref>Koltsida, 2008, p. 100</ref> During the interwar period it reached ca. 2,500 inhabitants that spoke Greek.<ref name=\"Hammond29213\">{{harvnb|Hammond|1967|pp=[https://books.google.gr/books?id=kEFoAAAAMAAJ&q=%22biggest,+Polican,+has+a+population+of+2,500+persons+and+Sopik+has+300+houses.%22&dq=%22biggest,+Polican,+has+a+population+of+2,500+persons+and+Sopik+has+300+houses.%22 29], 213}}</ref> but it decreased to 559 in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kallivretakis|first1=Leonidas|title=\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u039a\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c5\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0393\u03b5\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 [The Greek Community of Albania in Terms of Historical Geography and Demography]|url=http://helios-eie.ekt.gr/EIE/handle/10442/8696|publisher=\u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03a3\u03b9\u03b4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2|accessdate=2 February 2015|page=57|language=Greek|date=1995}}</ref>\n\n==Geography and culture==\nPolican is located on the slopes of [[Mount Nem\u00ebr\u00e7k\u00eb]], {{convert|13|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from the Greek-Albanian border.<ref name=enet/><ref name=\"Hammond213\"/> It is the northernmost Greek speaking village within the Pogoni region, which is divided between Greece (40 villages) and Albania (7 villages).<ref name=Giakoumis15/><ref name=Tziovas/><ref name=\"Hammond213\">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Epirus: the Geography, the Ancient Remains, the History and Topography of Epirus and Adjacent Areas|year=1967|location=Oxford|publisher=Clarendon Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=gI5QjgEACAAJ&dq=Epirus%3A+the+Geography%2C+the+Ancient+Remains&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Polican+therefore+regards+itself+as+the+most+northerly+village+of+the+area+Pogoni|isbn= 9780198142539|pages=213|ref=harv}} \"With a population of 2,500 Poli\u00e7an is the largest village in the long-rift within the double range of Nemer\u00e7k\u00eb. The villages to the north-west are Albanian-speaking, while those to the south speak Greek as their mother tongue. Poli\u00e7an therefore regards itself as the most northerly village of the area Pogoni.\"</ref> \n\nIn Polican, along with the rest of the Pogoni region, [[Polyphonic song of Epirus|polyphonic singing]] is part of the local musical tradition.<ref name=Tziovas>Tziovas, 2003, [https://books.google.gr/books?ei=GWLSVLTbAoaBU-TUgOAL&hl=el&id=s1VpAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22characterizes+many+local+communities%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Although+it+characterizes+many+local+communities+and+ethnic+groups%2C+such+as+Vlach+and+Albanian+speakers%2C+it+tends+to+be+mostly+identified+with+the+Pogoni+area%2C+which%2C+ironically+enough%2C+is+divided+between+Greece+and+Albania%2C+seven+villages+belonging+to+the+latter.+Of+the+rest%2C+about+forty+villages+belong+to+Greece+%28all+of+them+Greek-speaking%29%22 p. 196]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite web|last=Georgios|first=Giakoumis|script-title=el:\u0394\u03cd\u03bf \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03b9\u03bc\u03b1 \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1-\u0392\u03c5\u03b6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03ac \u039c\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf \u0396\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03c9\u03b3\u03ce\u03bd\u03b9 [Two Early Post-Byzantine Monuments and their Internal Enivironment in Pogoni] |publisher=[[University of Ioannina]]|accessdate=16 December 2014|pages=|year=2009 |language=Greek|format=pdf|url=http://phdtheses.ekt.gr/eadd/handle/10442/25277?locale=en}} (''PhD Thesis'')\n*{{cite book|last1=Hammond|first1=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Epirus: The Geography, the Ancient Remains, the History and Topography of Epirus and Adjacent Areas |date= 1967 |url= https://books.google.gr/books?ei=0yfRVKysCInyUKjCgMgB&hl=el&id=kEFoAAAAMAAJ&dq=|publisher=Clarendon P.}}\n*{{cite web|last=Koltsida|first=Athina|script-title=el:\u0397 \u0395\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u0392\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf \u0389\u03c0\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03bf \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u038e\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b7 \u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039f\u03b8\u03c9\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 [Education in Northern Epirus during the Latter Ottoman Period] |url=http://invenio.lib.auth.gr/record/104814?ln=el|publisher=[[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki]]|accessdate=16 December 2012|pages=|year=2008 |language=Greek|format=pdf}} (''PhD Thesis'')\n*{{cite book|last1=Tziovas|first1=edited by Dimitris|title=Greece and the Balkans: Identities, Perceptions and Cultural Encounters since the Enlightenment|date=2003|publisher=Ashgate|location=Aldershot, England|isbn=9780754609988|url=https://books.google.gr/books?ei=qn_WVMDwKtPkaMq6goAC&hl=el&id=s1VpAAAAMAAJ&dq=}}\n*\u0396\u03a9\u03a4\u039f\u03a5, \u039c\u0395\u039d\u0395\u039b\u0391\u039f\u03a5; \u0393\u0399\u0391\u039d\u039d\u0391\u03a1\u039f\u03a5, \u03a7\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u039f\u03a6\u039f\u03a1\u039f\u03a5. \u0397 \u03a0\u039f\u039b\u03a5\u03a4\u03a3\u0391\u039d\u0397 \u03a4\u0397\u03a3 \u0392\u039f\u03a1\u0395\u0399\u039f\u03a5 \u0397\u03a0\u0395\u0399\u03a1\u039f\u03a5. \u0395\u039a\u0394\u039f\u03a3\u0395\u0399\u03a3, \u0399\u03a9\u0391\u039d\u039d\u0399\u039d\u0391, 1989. \n*Politsanitika Nea Newspaper, Tel. +30 210 5238058 (Greek)\n\n==External links==\n\n===Traditional songs===\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zECQSPS1AjI \u0395\u03c8\u03ad\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c8\u03ad\u03c2 \u0391\u03c0\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c3\u03b1 &#91;One Night, Two Nights Ago I Dropped by&#93;].\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TuAfqnHUIY8 \u03a4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0393\u03b9\u03bf\u03c6\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03cd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 &#91;Song of the Bridge of Arta&#93;].\n\n===Website===\n*[http://www.politsani.com Politsani.com]\n\n{{Dropull div}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Polican, Gjirokaster}}\n\n[[Category:Greek communities in Albania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dropull]]\n[[Category:Villages in Gjirokast\u00ebr County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement AL\n|type               = v\n|official_name      = Poli\u00e7an\n|other_name         = \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03b7\n|image_flag         = \n|image_shield       = \n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_location     = \n|county             = [[Gjirokast\u00ebr County|Gjirokast\u00ebr]]\n|municipality       = [[Dropull]]\n|municunit          = [[Pogon, Albania|Pogon]]\n|leader_name        = \n|leader_party       = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|40|7|53|N|20|21|2|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = \n|population_as_of   = \n|population_total   = \n|postal_code        = \n|area_code          = \n|car_plates         = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Poli\u00e7an''' ({{lang-gr|\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03b7|Polytsani}}) is an ethnic Greek village in [[Gjirokast\u00ebr County]], southern [[Albania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geonames.org/search.html?q=Dervi\u00e7an&country=AL|accessdate=3 September 2010|title=Location of Dervi\u00e7an}}</ref> At the 2015 local government reform it became part of the municipality [[Dropull]].<ref>[http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf Law nr. 115/2014] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> It is within the wider Pogoni region that stretches in both [[Greece]] and Albania.<ref name=Giakoumis15/> Poli\u00e7an was the municipal center of the former [[Pogon, Albania|Pogon]] municipality in Albania. It is nicknamed \"the Bride of the Pogoni region\".<ref name=enet>{{cite web|last1=\u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5|first1=\u03a3\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03b1|title=\u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bb\u03b5\u03b3\u03b3\u03cd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03b7 \u03a0\u03c9\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03af\u03bf\u03c5|url=http://www.enet.gr/?i=news.el.article&id=444909|website=enet.gr|publisher=Eleftherotypia|accessdate=3 February 2015|language=Greek}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Antiquity and Byzantine period===\nIn classical antiquity the region was inhabited by the [[Chaonians]],<ref name=Giakoumis12/> one of the three major [[Ancient Greeks|Greek]] tribes that inhabited [[Epirus (ancient state)|ancient Epirus]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boardman|first1=John|last2=Hammond|first2=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=The Cambridge Ancient History - The Expansion of the Greek World, Eighth to Sixth Centuries B.C., Part 3: Volume 3|edition=Second|location=Cambridge, United Kingdom|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1982|isbn=0-521-23447-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qAoqP4g1fEC|ref=harv|pages=430, 434}}</ref> Polican was identified with the Chaonian settlement ''Politeiani'' ({{lang-el|\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u03ae}}) also known as ''Polyani'' ({{lang-el|\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03b1\u03bd\u03ae}}). The name appears to be borrowed from the nearby mountain Polyainos.<ref name=Giakoumis12/> Ancient coins depicting [[Alexander the Great]] have been unearthed in Poli\u00e7an.<ref>Hammond, 1967, [https://books.google.gr/books?ei=0yfRVKysCInyUKjCgMgB&hl=el&id=kEFoAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Polican%22+%22alexander+the+great%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Alexander+the+Great+at+Polican%2C+Vagalat+and+Phoenice%2C+later+kings+at+Dodona+and+Preveza%22 p. 722]</ref>\n\nThe ancient name has changed to the present form (Polyts(i)ani) during the [[Slavs|Slavic]] invasion (7th-8th century).<ref name=Giakoumis12>Giakoumis, 2009, p. 12</ref> In the late [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] period (11th-15th century) two Christian Orthodox monasteries were erected next to Polican.<ref name=Giakoumis12/> After the Fall of [[Constantinople]] in the [[Fourth Crusade]] (1204), Polican became part of the Greek [[Despotate of Epirus]] and refuge for various Byzantine noble families.<ref name=Giakoumis141>Giakoumis, 2009, p. 141</ref>\n\n===Ottoman period===\nAt the period of [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] occupation, that started in mid-15th century, Polican enjoyed a privileged semi-autonomous status which led to economic and cultural flourishing.<ref name=Giakoumis141/> The settlement was included in the [[Koinon of the Zagorisians|Koinon of Zagori]], although geographically it was not part of the [[Zagori]] region, but belonged to the Pogoni villages.<ref name=Giakoumis15>Giakoumis, 2009, p. 15</ref>\n\n[[File:Politsani Epirus 1931.jpg|thumbnail|Religious festival next to the church of Saint Nicholas in Polican, 1931]]\nIn the early 16th century two significant church buildings were erected in the town: Saint Athanasius (1513) and Saint Demetrius (1526). Both of them display unique features of early post-Byzantine art.<ref>Giakoumis, 2009, p. 139</ref> A Greek school was founded in 1672 by the local Orthodox missionary [[Sophianos of Dryinoupolis|Sophianos]] next to the church of Saint Athanasius.<ref name=Koltsida131>Koltsida, 2008, p. 131</ref> The school attracted also students from the nearby regions next to [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]] ([[Zagori, Albania|Zagori]] and Riza).<ref>Koltsida, 2008, p. 197</ref>\n\nA second school started operating in 1750, sponsored by a local businessman and benefactor.<ref name=Koltsida131/> Greek education was expanded with the foundation of two secondary level schools in 1866, in addition to a boys' and a girls' school in 1866 and 1874 respectively.<ref>Koltsida, 2008, p. 229</ref> The local educational institutions became renowned to such a degree that their graduates were eligible for admission to any Greek college in the Ottoman capital [[Constantinople]] ([[Istanbul]]) without qualifying examinations.<ref>Koltsida, 2008, p. 235</ref> The schools of Polican were financed by the local community and especially by local businessmen and benefactors as well as by the town's diaspora.<ref>Koltsida, 2008, pp. 281&ndash;285</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nPolican and the rest of the settlements in the Pogon municipality became part of [[Albania]] in the 1920s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=(Eds.)|first1=Andreas Hemming ...|title=Albania : family, society and culture in the 20th century|date=2010|publisher=LIT|location=M\u00fcnster [u.a.]|isbn=9783643501448|page=103|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=HfpTqhlsCtMC&pg=PA103}}</ref> In 1940, when [[Kingdom of Italy|Axis Italy]] launched a [[Greco-Italian War|failed invasion against Greece]] from Albanian territory during [[World War II]], the town came under the control of the [[II Army Corps (Greece)|II Army Corps]] of the Greek forces.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carr|first1=John C.|title=The defence and fall of Greece 1940-1941|date=2013|isbn=9781781591819|pages=82\u201383|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=2Zb9AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA82&dq=1940+polican&hl=el&sa=X&ei=aTfOVKf8C8z3UuXtgdAB&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=1940%20polican&f=false}}</ref>\n\nThe Greek communities that reside in Pogon have a recognized minority status by the Albanian state.<ref>Tziovas, 2003, [https://books.google.gr/books?ei=qn_WVMDwKtPkaMq6goAC&hl=el&id=s1VpAAAAMAAJ&dq=pogon+greek+minority&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Apart+from+the+ethnic+Greek+communities+that+are+officially+recognized+as+a+minority+and+comprise+a+clear+and+largely+homogeneous+zone%2C+namely+the+rural+areas+of+Dropul%2C+Sarandi+and+Pogon%2C+the+situation+is+still+quite+complex+in+terms+of%22 p. 196]</ref> A Greek elementary school is currently operating in Polican.<ref>{{cite web|title=Second Report Submitted by Albania Pursuant to Article 25, Paragraph 2 of the Framework onvention for the Protection of National Minorities|url=https://www.coe.int/t/dghl/monitoring/minorities/3_FCNMdocs/PDF_2nd_SR_Albania_en.pdf|website=Council of Europe|accessdate=7 February 2015|page=62}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 1913 the population of Polican  was 1,650 (Greek census).<ref>Koltsida, 2008, p. 100</ref> During the interwar period it reached ca. 2,500 inhabitants that spoke Greek.<ref name=\"Hammond29213\">{{harvnb|Hammond|1967|pp=[https://books.google.gr/books?id=kEFoAAAAMAAJ&q=%22biggest,+Polican,+has+a+population+of+2,500+persons+and+Sopik+has+300+houses.%22&dq=%22biggest,+Polican,+has+a+population+of+2,500+persons+and+Sopik+has+300+houses.%22 29], 213}}</ref> but it decreased to 559 in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kallivretakis|first1=Leonidas|title=\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u039a\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c5\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0393\u03b5\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 [The Greek Community of Albania in Terms of Historical Geography and Demography]|url=http://helios-eie.ekt.gr/EIE/handle/10442/8696|publisher=\u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03a3\u03b9\u03b4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2|accessdate=2 February 2015|page=57|language=Greek|date=1995}}</ref>\n\n==Geography and culture==\nPolican is located on the slopes of [[Mount Nem\u00ebr\u00e7k\u00eb]], {{convert|13|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from the Greek-Albanian border.<ref name=enet/><ref name=\"Hammond213\"/> It is the northernmost Greek speaking village within the Pogoni region, which is divided between Greece (40 villages) and Albania (7 villages).<ref name=Giakoumis15/><ref name=Tziovas/><ref name=\"Hammond213\">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Epirus: the Geography, the Ancient Remains, the History and Topography of Epirus and Adjacent Areas|year=1967|location=Oxford|publisher=Clarendon Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=gI5QjgEACAAJ&dq=Epirus%3A+the+Geography%2C+the+Ancient+Remains&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Polican+therefore+regards+itself+as+the+most+northerly+village+of+the+area+Pogoni|isbn= 9780198142539|pages=213|ref=harv}} \"With a population of 2,500 Poli\u00e7an is the largest village in the long-rift within the double range of Nemer\u00e7k\u00eb. The villages to the north-west are Albanian-speaking, while those to the south speak Greek as their mother tongue. Poli\u00e7an therefore regards itself as the most northerly village of the area Pogoni.\"</ref> \n\nIn Polican, along with the rest of the Pogoni region, [[Polyphonic song of Epirus|polyphonic singing]] is part of the local musical tradition.<ref name=Tziovas>Tziovas, 2003, [https://books.google.gr/books?ei=GWLSVLTbAoaBU-TUgOAL&hl=el&id=s1VpAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22characterizes+many+local+communities%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Although+it+characterizes+many+local+communities+and+ethnic+groups%2C+such+as+Vlach+and+Albanian+speakers%2C+it+tends+to+be+mostly+identified+with+the+Pogoni+area%2C+which%2C+ironically+enough%2C+is+divided+between+Greece+and+Albania%2C+seven+villages+belonging+to+the+latter.+Of+the+rest%2C+about+forty+villages+belong+to+Greece+%28all+of+them+Greek-speaking%29%22 p. 196]</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Sophianos of Dryinoupolis|Sophianos]] (-1711), Greek-Orthodox bishop and scholar.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite web|last=Georgios|first=Giakoumis|script-title=el:\u0394\u03cd\u03bf \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03b9\u03bc\u03b1 \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1-\u0392\u03c5\u03b6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03ac \u039c\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf \u0396\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03c9\u03b3\u03ce\u03bd\u03b9 [Two Early Post-Byzantine Monuments and their Internal Enivironment in Pogoni] |publisher=[[University of Ioannina]]|accessdate=16 December 2014|pages=|year=2009 |language=Greek|format=pdf|url=http://phdtheses.ekt.gr/eadd/handle/10442/25277?locale=en}} (''PhD Thesis'')\n*{{cite book|last1=Hammond|first1=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Epirus: The Geography, the Ancient Remains, the History and Topography of Epirus and Adjacent Areas |date= 1967 |url= https://books.google.gr/books?ei=0yfRVKysCInyUKjCgMgB&hl=el&id=kEFoAAAAMAAJ&dq=|publisher=Clarendon P.}}\n*{{cite web|last=Koltsida|first=Athina|script-title=el:\u0397 \u0395\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u0392\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf \u0389\u03c0\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03bf \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u038e\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b7 \u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039f\u03b8\u03c9\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 [Education in Northern Epirus during the Latter Ottoman Period] |url=http://invenio.lib.auth.gr/record/104814?ln=el|publisher=[[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki]]|accessdate=16 December 2012|pages=|year=2008 |language=Greek|format=pdf}} (''PhD Thesis'')\n*{{cite book|last1=Tziovas|first1=edited by Dimitris|title=Greece and the Balkans: Identities, Perceptions and Cultural Encounters since the Enlightenment|date=2003|publisher=Ashgate|location=Aldershot, England|isbn=9780754609988|url=https://books.google.gr/books?ei=qn_WVMDwKtPkaMq6goAC&hl=el&id=s1VpAAAAMAAJ&dq=}}\n*\u0396\u03a9\u03a4\u039f\u03a5, \u039c\u0395\u039d\u0395\u039b\u0391\u039f\u03a5; \u0393\u0399\u0391\u039d\u039d\u0391\u03a1\u039f\u03a5, \u03a7\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u039f\u03a6\u039f\u03a1\u039f\u03a5. \u0397 \u03a0\u039f\u039b\u03a5\u03a4\u03a3\u0391\u039d\u0397 \u03a4\u0397\u03a3 \u0392\u039f\u03a1\u0395\u0399\u039f\u03a5 \u0397\u03a0\u0395\u0399\u03a1\u039f\u03a5. \u0395\u039a\u0394\u039f\u03a3\u0395\u0399\u03a3, \u0399\u03a9\u0391\u039d\u039d\u0399\u039d\u0391, 1989. \n*Politsanitika Nea Newspaper, Tel. +30 210 5238058 (Greek)\n\n==External links==\n\n===Traditional songs===\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zECQSPS1AjI \u0395\u03c8\u03ad\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c8\u03ad\u03c2 \u0391\u03c0\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c3\u03b1 &#91;One Night, Two Nights Ago I Dropped by&#93;].\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TuAfqnHUIY8 \u03a4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0393\u03b9\u03bf\u03c6\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03cd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 &#91;Song of the Bridge of Arta&#93;].\n\n===Website===\n*[http://www.politsani.com Politsani.com]\n\n{{Dropull div}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Polican, Gjirokaster}}\n\n[[Category:Greek communities in Albania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dropull]]\n[[Category:Villages in Gjirokast\u00ebr County]]\n", "name_user": "217.73.141.208", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poli%C3%A7an,_Gjirokast%C3%ABr"}
